 the debt of their salvation. Ryan traces the ideas that shaped “disposal” policies towards liberated Africans, and the forms of resistance and accommodation that characterized their responses. This book demonstrates the impact of interventionist experiments on the lives of the liberated people, on the evolution of a British antislavery “world system,” and on the emergence of modern understandings of refuge, asylum, and humanitarian governance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2022) 0aAntislavery movementszGreat BritainxHistory. 0aFreed personszAfrica. 0aHumanitarian assistance, BritishxHistory. 0aSlave tradezGreat Britain. 0aSlaveryzGreat Britain. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Slavery.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311074977940uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030026560640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300265606423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300265606/original  a978-3-11-074977-9  Yale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles